    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "W6",
  "trapSubtype": "Base Rate Neglect",
  "causalStructure": "The hit rate P(Y|X) is presented without accounting for the extreme base rate P(Y); macro shock regime can also influence both X and Y, but the key failure is ignoring priors when inferring that flagged events are likely de-pegs.",
  "keyInsight": "A high hit rate can still produce mostly false alarms when the event’s base rate is tiny.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Did the signal trigger before the stablecoin began drifting from $1, or was it computed using order flow after the initial price deviation started?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If the signal also has an extremely low false-positive rate (e.g., it triggers on <0.1% of non-de-peg days), then the claim would be more plausible because the posterior P(de-peg|signal) could become meaningfully high despite the low base rate.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If the signal triggers frequently (e.g., on 5–10% of all days), then the claim is not supported because with a 0.4% base rate, most signal days will be non-de-peg days even if P(signal|de-peg) is high."
  },
  "explanation": "The scenario gives an impressive conditional probability (“85% of the time”) but also states an extreme prior: de-pegs happened on only 0.4% of days. Concluding that the signal ‘predicts’ or ‘causes’ de-pegs ignores that a rare outcome requires exceptionally low false positives to yield a high posterior probability. Proper Bayesian reasoning could imply that most signal triggers are false alarms, so the causal conclusion is not justified.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This conclusion neglects the base rate. The scenario highlights an 85% hit rate—“when the exchange’s ‘merger-arb imbalance’ signal triggers, the stablecoin de-pegs… 85% of the time”—but also states the prior is extreme: “De-pegs… occurred on only 0.4% of days.” With such a tiny base rate, even a seemingly strong hit rate can still correspond to a low probability that a triggered signal day is truly a de-peg day unless false positives are near-zero. Therefore you can’t infer the signal causes (or even reliably implies) an imminent de-peg from the hit rate alone.",
