  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is confounder–mediator confusion: you can’t justify the intervention effect after “controlling for” Z without knowing whether Z is pre- or post-treatment. The scenario explicitly says they \"control for\" a same-day composite called \"FDA sentiment\" built from \"FDA briefing headlines and analyst notes,\" which can be updated after the earnings release. If the earnings announcement changes perceived FDA risk (X→Z→Y), adjusting for Z removes a real causal pathway and makes the spillover look artificially small. Without establishing whether Z occurs before or after the intervention, the claim that the effect is only marginal is unsupported.",
