  "explanation": "The analysts assume the “risk-off sentiment index” is a pre-treatment confounder, but in a market correction it can also be a post-announcement reaction channel through which purchases affect yields. Because the scenario does not establish whether the index is measured/realized before the purchase expansion or after it, conditioning on it can either remove spurious correlation or remove real causal impact.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is confounder–mediator confusion: the analysis assumes Z is a confounder without establishing whether it occurs before or after the intervention. The scenario says they “treat the index as a pre-policy confounder” and that “yields fell most in weeks when a ‘risk-off sentiment index’ spiked,” but during a correction the index could itself move in response to the Central Bank’s purchase expansion. If Z is affected by X, adjusting for Z can strip out part of QE’s real effect on yields, so the ‘only 8 bps’ conclusion is not justified.",
