  "goldRationale": "The claim assumes X→Y: increasing FX-hedge swap activity tightens CDS and lowers funding costs. However, the market microstructure and credit-channel mechanism plausibly run Y→X. When ABC’s perceived creditworthiness improves after the executive change/policy repricing (Z), its CDS tightens and wholesale funding costs fall (Y). That same improvement relaxes dealer balance-sheet constraints, CSA haircuts, initial margin, and credit limits, letting ABC execute/roll larger swap notionals at tighter basis (X). The observed co-movement (CDS tighter when swap-implied funding spread narrows) is therefore compatible with credit improvement enabling hedging capacity rather than hedging causing credit improvement. An intervention that mandates larger swap notionals may simply increase gross exposures, collateral needs, or costs without changing fundamentals; hence the causal effect on Y is not justified. To justify X→Y, one would need evidence that the swap program reduces a specific, model-relevant unhedged FX mismatch and that this fundamental risk reduction precedes and predicts CDS tightening independent of contemporaneous credit repricing and dealer constraints.",
