  "variables": {
    "X": {
      "name": "Stock split announcement by BioTech Start",
      "role": "exposure"
    },
    "Y": {
      "name": "BioTech Start share price performance in the weeks after the announcement",
      "role": "outcome"
    },
    "Z": [
      "Trading liquidity and investor base composition (generalist fund participation) that co-moves with both price and split decisions"
    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "T11",
  "trapSubtype": "Feedback Loop",
  "causalStructure": "X can affect Y via liquidity/investor attention (X→Z→Y), but Y also affects Z and the propensity/ability to do X (Y→Z and Y→X), creating a reinforcing loop between split decisions, liquidity, and price.",
  "keyInsight": "When splits, liquidity, and price reinforce each other, you can’t treat the split as a one-way lever on price.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Did Pharma Inc’s price strength and liquidity begin improving before the split announcement (e.g., during the sector rotation), making the split partly a response to already-rising demand?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If BioTech Start’s split is exogenous (e.g., mandated by listing rules or pre-set in a financing covenant) and not triggered by prior price/interest, then the answer is still uncertain but more plausible because the Y→X feedback is reduced.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If BioTech Start chooses the split because its shares are already rallying into the FDA meeting and liquidity is already improving, then NO because the observed association likely reflects the reinforcing Y→X and Y→Z pathways rather than a clean X→Y effect."
  },
  "explanation": "The scenario embeds a bidirectional dynamic: a split can increase liquidity and broaden the buyer base (supporting price), but rising price and improving liquidity also motivate and enable management/owners to do a split to accommodate demand. The claim assumes only split→price and ignores that the split decision and post-split flows may be partly consequences of pre-existing price strength and investor attention, especially around an FDA catalyst during sector rotation.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is a feedback-loop error: it treats the stock split as a one-way cause of price when price and liquidity can also drive the split decision. The scenario notes that after Pharma Inc’s split, \"shares held up and trading liquidity improved, attracting more generalist funds\" and that BioTech Start will split \"ahead of an FDA meeting\" during a rotation—conditions where rising demand/price and improving liquidity can both (i) prompt a split and (ii) amplify post-split buying. Because X and Y can reinforce each other through liquidity and investor participation, the proportional intervention effect is not justified.",
  "goldRationale": "To justify the intervention claim, we would need a setting where the split is plausibly exogenous to prior price momentum and investor demand. Here, there are credible mechanisms in both directions: (1) X→Y: a split can lower the per-share price, tighten spreads, and increase retail/options participation, improving liquidity and potentially supporting price. (2) Y→X (and Y→Z): when a stock is already strong—especially into an FDA catalyst—management and PE sponsors are more likely to split to accommodate higher volumes and broaden the investor base; that same strength attracts generalist funds and improves liquidity. This mutual reinforcement means the observed post-split resilience at Pharma Inc could be partly because the stock was already benefiting from rotation and demand, not because the split mechanically created value. Therefore, inferring that doing a split will cause BioTech Start’s price to rise is not warranted without disentangling the loop (e.g., using pre-announced split schedules, instruments, or event-study controls for pre-trends and catalyst-driven demand).",
  "difficulty": "Medium"
}

{
  "scenario": "In H2 2023, after a hotter-than-expected US inflation print, regulators signaled tighter stablecoin compliance checks. A Crypto Exchange noticed that DeFi Protocols listing more of its preferred Stablecoin saw higher spot and perp volumes on the exchange. During an acquisition offer for a small DeFi Protocol, the exchange’s strategy memo says: “If we force the protocol to adopt our stablecoin as the default, exchange volume will rise.”",
  "claim": "Forcing the acquired DeFi Protocol to adopt the Crypto Exchange’s preferred Stablecoin as the default settlement asset causes the Crypto Exchange’s trading volume to rise.",
  "variables": {
    "X": {
      "name": "Mandating the DeFi Protocol’s default stablecoin to be the exchange-preferred Stablecoin",
      "role": "exposure"
    },
    "Y": {
      "name": "Crypto Exchange trading volume (spot + perpetuals) in H2 2023",
      "role": "outcome"
    },
    "Z": [
      "Mutual reinforcement between exchange volume/liquidity and stablecoin adoption/availability across venues"
    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "T11",
  "trapSubtype": "Feedback Loop",
  "causalStructure": "X can increase Y by reducing friction and concentrating liquidity (X→Y), but higher Y also increases stablecoin adoption on the protocol by improving liquidity, incentives, and market-maker support (Y→X); the observed association reflects a loop, so a one-way intervention claim is not identified.",
  "keyInsight": "When adoption and liquidity feed each other, you can’t treat the relationship as one-directional and expect a clean intervention effect.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Did DeFi Protocols increase use of the preferred Stablecoin before the exchange’s volume rose, or did volume/liquidity rise first and then make that stablecoin more attractive to use?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If the exchange could hold exchange liquidity, market-maker incentives, and stablecoin on/off-ramp access fixed while only changing the protocol’s default, then the effect is more likely YES because that isolates the X→Y channel (reduced friction driving volume).",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If higher exchange volume is what previously enabled the stablecoin to become the protocol default via deeper liquidity and incentives, then NO because the apparent X→Y pattern is largely Y→X feedback rather than a standalone intervention effect."
  },
  "explanation": "The memo infers that mandating stablecoin usage on the DeFi Protocol will raise the exchange’s volume because protocols that already use the stablecoin are correlated with higher volume. But exchange volume itself plausibly drives stablecoin adoption by attracting market makers, deepening liquidity, and making the stablecoin easier/cheaper to use—creating a reinforcing loop that the one-way intervention claim ignores.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is a feedback-loop trap: the scenario supports bidirectional causation, so the one-way intervention claim isn’t justified. The memo cites that “DeFi Protocols listing more of its preferred Stablecoin saw higher spot and perp volumes,” but higher exchange volume can itself make that stablecoin easier to use (better liquidity, tighter spreads, more incentives), which then increases adoption on protocols. Because X and Y can reinforce each other, forcing X doesn’t guarantee the same Y increase seen in the correlation.",
  "goldRationale": "To evaluate the intervention “mandate the stablecoin as default” (X) on exchange volume (Y), we must consider that (1) X→Y is plausible: standardizing on one stablecoin can reduce settlement friction, concentrate liquidity, and increase arbitrage/hedging flows that boost volume. However, (2) Y→X is also plausible and hinted by market microstructure: when the exchange already has high volume, market makers deploy more capital, spreads tighten, and on/off-ramps for that stablecoin improve, making protocols more willing to adopt it as default. The scenario’s evidence is an association across protocols, not an identified one-way causal effect. With a reinforcing loop, an intervention on X may be partially offset or amplified depending on whether Y-endogenous drivers (liquidity programs, compliance constraints after the economic data, market-maker participation) also move. Therefore the proportional “mandate causes volume to rise” claim is not justified without breaking or modeling the feedback dynamics (e.g., exogenous rollout, randomized/default assignment, or controls for liquidity/incentives that drive adoption).",
  "difficulty": "Easy"
}

{
