  "keyInsight": "When treatment changes a covariate that later drives both future treatment dynamics and outcomes, “adjusting for the covariate” can bias the estimated intervention effect.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Does the causal structure change over time—i.e., does the split change week-1 retail flow, which then changes week-2 liquidity and subsequent split-related buying that affects week-4 returns?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If retail-flow and liquidity were fully pre-treatment and not affected by the split (measured strictly before the announcement), then the adjustment would be less problematic and the outperformance estimate could be closer to causal.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If you model the dynamic process with appropriate longitudinal causal methods (e.g., marginal structural models with inverse probability weights) and still find a robust effect, then a causal claim would be more defensible because time-varying confounding is addressed."
  },
  "explanation": "The note adjusts for weekly retail-flow intensity, but the scenario states the split itself increases retail flow in week 1. That flow then influences later liquidity and subsequent trading behavior (future exposure intensity) and ultimately returns. This is classic time-varying confounding affected by prior treatment: naive regression/adjustment for post-treatment flow and liquidity can block part of the split’s effect and/or open biasing paths.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is time-varying confounding: the split affects covariates that later influence both subsequent treatment dynamics and the outcome. The scenario says the estimate was obtained “after controlling for weekly retail-flow intensity,” yet also that “the split itself boosted retail-flow in week 1, which influenced whether market makers tightened spreads in week 2 and also affected split-driven momentum into week 4.” Because retail flow and liquidity are post-split variables that help determine later trading conditions and returns, standard adjustment for them can bias the estimated intervention effect, so the 6% outperformance claim is not justified.",
  "goldRationale": "To justify an intervention claim (“doing the split causes +6% relative return”), we need an identification strategy that handles longitudinal dependencies. Here, X (split) changes Z over time: X → retail flow (week 1) → liquidity/spreads (week 2) → continued split-related demand/market-maker behavior (later weeks) → Y (1-month relative return). Meanwhile, those time-varying Z variables also affect subsequent exposure-like dynamics (how much split-driven demand persists) and directly affect Y. Regressing Y on X while controlling for weekly retail-flow intensity (a post-treatment variable) generally produces biased estimates: it can block part of the causal pathway (mediation through attention/liquidity) and can induce collider/selection effects in the presence of time-varying confounding where Z predicts future treatment intensity. Proper analysis would require longitudinal causal methods (e.g., g-methods such as marginal structural models) or using strictly pre-announcement covariates/instruments; absent that, the claimed causal effect is not supported.",
  "difficulty": "Medium"
}

{
  "scenario": "In H2 2023, after an unexpected US inflation print, a major crypto exchange received an acquisition offer and rushed a new “enhanced compliance mode” for accounts that opt in. Post-launch reports show opt-in accounts have 30% fewer stablecoin (USDC) AML alerts and fewer DeFi-protocol exposure flags. But enhanced mode uses a new chain-analytics vendor that auto-whitelists some stablecoin transfers and suppresses “low-confidence” DeFi labels, while non–opt-in accounts keep the old, noisier rules.",
