      "role": "exposure"
    },
    "Y": {
      "name": "Rate of flagged stablecoin AML alerts and DeFi-protocol exposure flags",
      "role": "outcome"
    },
    "Z": [
      "Different monitoring/measurement system accuracy (new vendor with whitelisting and low-confidence suppression vs legacy rules)"
    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "T13",
  "trapSubtype": "Measurement Bias",
  "causalStructure": "X changes the measurement process Z (new vendor rules), and Z directly changes observed Y (flag counts) without necessarily changing true underlying illicit activity or DeFi exposure.",
  "keyInsight": "A drop in “flags” can be an artifact when the flagging system itself changes only for the treated group.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Did the exchange switch to the new chain-analytics vendor only after accounts opted into enhanced compliance mode in H2 2023?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If both opt-in and non–opt-in accounts were evaluated using the same monitoring rules/vendor (or the old rules were replayed on the opt-in accounts), then the estimated effect could be answerable because Y would be measured comparably across groups.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If enhanced compliance mode only changed back-end detection thresholds/whitelisting (without changing user behavior or enforcement), then the observed 30% reduction is not evidence of a real compliance improvement because it reflects differential measurement, not a causal change in true risk."
  },
  "explanation": "The intervention (enhanced compliance mode) is bundled with a different detection stack that systematically under-flags certain stablecoin transfers and suppresses low-confidence DeFi labels. Because treated accounts are measured with a more permissive/filtered system than untreated accounts, the observed reduction in alerts can be fully explained by differential measurement rather than a real reduction in suspicious activity.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is differential measurement (measurement bias): the outcome is not measured the same way in treated vs untreated accounts. The scenario states that “enhanced mode uses a new chain-analytics vendor that auto-whitelists some stablecoin transfers and suppresses ‘low-confidence’ DeFi labels, while non–opt-in accounts keep the old, noisier rules.” That means the 30% drop in alerts/flags could be caused by the new labeling and whitelisting logic rather than any true reduction in illicit stablecoin activity or DeFi exposure, so the intervention effect is not justified.",
  "goldRationale": "To justify the claim, we need the intervention X to change the underlying compliance reality (true suspicious activity/exposure), not merely how it is detected and counted. Here, X changes Z—the measurement pipeline—only for opt-in accounts. Z then mechanically reduces observed Y by (i) whitelisting certain stablecoin flows (fewer AML alerts) and (ii) suppressing low-confidence DeFi labels (fewer DeFi exposure flags). This is systematic (not random) error, it differs by treatment status (opt-in vs not), and the bias direction is downward for the treated group (under-counting flags), creating a spurious “improvement.” Without standardized measurement (same vendor/rules applied to both groups or back-testing both rule sets on the same transactions), the causal claim that rolling out enhanced compliance mode reduces risk/flags is unsupported.",
  "difficulty": "Medium"
}

