      "role": "exposure"
    },
    "Y": {
      "name": "Observed bid–ask spread on green sovereign bonds",
      "role": "outcome"
    },
    "Z": [
      "Quote/price measurement system (real-time mandatory venue reporting vs delayed OTC composite prints)"
    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "T13",
  "trapSubtype": "Measurement Bias (differential outcome measurement by treatment status)",
  "causalStructure": "X changes the measurement process Z (venue with mandatory real-time quotes), and Z systematically affects the observed Y (measured spreads), creating an apparent spread tightening even if true liquidity/spreads do not improve.",
  "keyInsight": "When treated assets are measured with higher-frequency, more transparent quotes, “improved spreads” can be a reporting artifact rather than a real intervention effect.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Did the move to the Central Bank reporting venue occur at the same time as facility eligibility, before the observed 18 bps tightening was calculated?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If spreads for eligible and non-eligible bonds were computed from the same microstructure data source (same venue, same timestamping, same quote requirements), then the intervention could be evaluated more credibly because differential measurement would be removed.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If eligible bonds are measured with real-time executable quotes while non-eligible bonds use delayed OTC composites, then NO because the 18 bps difference can be driven by systematic measurement differences rather than true spread changes."
  },
  "explanation": "The reported outcome (bid–ask spreads) is not measured equivalently across treatment groups. Facility-eligible bonds are observed on a venue with mandatory real-time quoting, which tends to record tighter, more current executable spreads. Non-eligible bonds are observed via delayed composite prints that can overstate spreads. This differential accuracy creates a spurious “effect” attributed to the facility.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is differential measurement bias (T13): the outcome is measured more accurately for treated bonds. The scenario states that facility-eligible bonds were \"moved onto a new Central Bank reporting venue with mandatory real-time quotes,\" while non-eligible bonds \"remained largely OTC with delayed, end-of-day composite prints.\" Because the bid–ask spread is being captured using different data-generation/measurement systems across groups, the 18 bps tightening can be an artifact of improved quote visibility/timestamping rather than a true liquidity improvement caused by expanding the facility.",
  "goldRationale": "At L2 (intervention), the claim requires that doing X (expanding facility eligibility) would change the true bid–ask spreads Y. But the scenario embeds that X changes how Y is observed: eligibility coincides with migration to a reporting venue with mandatory real-time quotes. This creates systematic, treatment-dependent measurement error: eligible bonds’ spreads are derived from live executable quotes (typically tighter and more precise), while non-eligible bonds’ spreads are inferred from delayed OTC composites (often wider/lagged). The bias direction is determinable: better, real-time quote data will generally reduce measured spreads relative to delayed composites, producing an apparent tightening for treated bonds even if true spreads are unchanged. Therefore the observed 18 bps difference does not justify the causal intervention claim without harmonized measurement or a design that separates facility effects from reporting/measurement changes.",
