  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is a measurement-bias trap: the intervention changes how defaults are measured, not necessarily the underlying defaults. The scenario says the scoring “automatically pulls Insurance Corp claim histories and Credit Agency bureau files” and then “reports a weekly ‘default-rate’ KPI,” while others are implicitly not measured the same way. If treated clients have more complete/earlier delinquency detection (and untreated clients have delayed or noisier recognition), the observed 30% drop can be an artifact of differential measurement/timing rather than a causal reduction in true defaults.",
  "goldRationale": "At L2, the claim requires that intervening on X would change Y. But here X directly affects Z: the accuracy and timing of outcome ascertainment. After the policy shift and during the IPO quarter, Bank ABC’s scored segment gets automated bureau/claims integrations that can (i) reclassify borderline delinquencies, (ii) change the event-time used for “default” in weekly reporting, and (iii) reduce missingness relative to manual reconciliation in the unscored segment. Because this measurement error is systematic and differs by treatment status, the measured default-rate KPI is not comparable across groups. The direction is determinable: the treated group is monitored more frequently and with richer feeds, making its KPI mechanically different from the untreated group’s lagged/partial capture; thus the reported 30% improvement can be partially or fully artifactual. Without harmonizing default definitions, data sources, and reporting lags (or validating against a common ground-truth ledger), the causal intervention claim is not justified.",
