    "X": {
      "name": "Smart-order routing toggle enabled",
      "role": "exposure"
    },
    "Y": {
      "name": "Slippage on stablecoin trades (bps)",
      "role": "outcome"
    },
    "Z": [
      "Trade-execution measurement granularity (ms-level fill logs vs 1-second aggregated logs)"
    ]
  },
  "groundTruth": "NO",
  "trapType": "T13",
  "trapSubtype": "Measurement Bias",
  "causalStructure": "X changes how slippage is measured/recorded (Z); Z systematically biases observed Y downward for treated users even if true slippage is unchanged, creating an apparent X→Y effect.",
  "keyInsight": "An intervention can look effective when it mainly improves (or changes) the measurement of the outcome in the treated group.",
  "hiddenTimestamp": "Were the ms-level fill logs and fee capture turned on only after enabling routing, while the control group kept the coarser 1-second aggregation during the same H2 2023 window?",
  "conditionalAnswers": {
    "answer_if_condition_1": "If both groups’ slippage were computed from the same raw data (same timestamp resolution, identical fee/partial-fill capture), then the answer could be YES because the observed reduction would no longer be attributable to differential measurement.",
    "answer_if_condition_2": "If routed trades also had additional hidden costs (e.g., higher taker fees) that were excluded only from the routed slippage calculation, then the answer is even more strongly NO because the 18% improvement would be mechanically inflated by asymmetric accounting."
  },
  "explanation": "The treated group (routing enabled) is evaluated with more complete execution data (ms timestamps, full fill breakdowns), while the untreated group’s executions are measured with coarser aggregation that misses partial fills and some fees. Because the outcome is computed differently by treatment status, the 18% ‘slippage improvement’ can be an artifact of differential measurement rather than a true causal effect of routing.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is measurement bias: the outcome is not measured the same way across treated and untreated users. The scenario notes that “only routed orders were logged with millisecond timestamps and full fill breakdowns” while “non-routed orders were aggregated into 1-second buckets, missing partial fills and some fees.” That differential accuracy can mechanically make routed users’ reported slippage look lower, so the 18% drop cannot be attributed to the routing toggle without a standardized slippage calculation.",
  "goldRationale": "To justify the causal claim (do X → Y), Y must be comparably measured across treatment groups. Here, enabling routing changes the logging pipeline: routed trades have higher-resolution timestamps and more complete capture of partial fills/fees, while non-routed trades are coarsely aggregated and miss components that affect realized execution price. This is systematic (not random) and differs by treatment status, satisfying differential measurement error. The bias direction is determinable: missing partial fills/fees in the control can distort computed slippage relative to the treated group; with more complete accounting for routed trades, the reported metric can shift downward (or the control can be overstated/understated), producing a spurious ‘improvement’ that is partially or fully artifactual. Therefore, the observed 18% reduction does not identify the intervention effect of routing.",
  "difficulty": "Medium"
}

