  "explanation": "Exposure (duration risk-taking) is collected retrospectively via a survey administered after dealers know whether they lost money in the correction. Loss-making desks are more likely to search for explanations and over-report risky positioning, while profitable desks may under-report or forget it. This differential recall inflates the apparent benefit of an intervention that forces duration cuts.",
  "wiseRefusal": "NO. This is recall bias: the “exposure” is reconstructed after outcomes are known, so outcome knowledge can distort memory of exposure. The scenario says dealers were surveyed “in June, after P&L was known, asking them to recall whether they had ‘extended duration’… before each selloff,” and the conclusion relies on self-reports like “worst correction losses reported 68%… profitable desks reported 29%.” Because losers may remember/attribute losses to having been long duration more than winners do, the 68% vs 29% difference can be a reporting artifact, so the intervention effect claim is not justified.",
